Certainly! I'd be happy to help you get started with creating a 2D game in Java. Here's a basic framework to set up a game window using Java's Swing library:

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;

public class Game2D extends JPanel {

    public Game2D() {
        setPreferredSize(new Dimension(800, 600));
    }

    @Override
    protected void paintComponent(Graphics g) {
        super.paintComponent(g);
        // Game rendering code will go here
    }

    public void update() {
        // Game logic update code will go here
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        JFrame frame = new JFrame("2D Game");
        Game2D game = new Game2D();
        frame.add(game);
        frame.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        frame.pack();
        frame.setVisible(true);

        // Game loop
        while (true) {
            game.update();
            game.repaint();
            try {
                Thread.sleep(16); // Approx. 60 FPS
            } catch (InterruptedException e) {
                e.printStackTrace();
            }
        }
    }
}
```

This code sets up a basic game window and a game loop. Here's what it does:

1. Creates a JPanel subclass called Game2D where we'll do our drawing.
2. Sets up a main method that creates a JFrame and adds our Game2D panel to it.
3. Implements a simple game loop that calls update() and repaint() methods 60 times per second.

To start building your game:
1. Add game objects and logic in the update() method.
2. Draw your game elements in the paintComponent() method.
3. Add keyboard and mouse input handling.

