Certainly! I can help you output the current FPS to the console. To do this, we'll need to modify the `run()` method in your `GamePanel` class. Here's how you can implement it:

1. First, add a variable to keep track of the frame count:

```java
private int frameCount = 0;
```

2. Then, modify the `run()` method to calculate and output the FPS:

```java
@Override
public void run() {
    double drawInterval = 1000000000 / FPS;
    double nextDrawTime = System.nanoTime() + drawInterval;
    long lastFPSCheck = System.nanoTime();

    while (gameThread != null) {
        update();
        repaint();
        frameCount++;

        try {
            double remainingTime = nextDrawTime - System.nanoTime();
            remainingTime = remainingTime / 1000000;

            if (remainingTime < 0) {
                System.out.println("Frame took longer than expected to render");
                remainingTime = 0;
            }
            Thread.sleep((long) remainingTime);
            nextDrawTime += drawInterval;

            // Calculate and output FPS every second
            if (System.nanoTime() - lastFPSCheck >= 1000000000) {
                System.out.println("Current FPS: " + frameCount);
                frameCount = 0;
                lastFPSCheck = System.nanoTime();
            }

        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            System.out.println("Thread Interrupted");
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
```

This modification will output the current FPS to the console every second. The `frameCount` variable keeps track of how many frames have been rendered, and it's reset every second when the FPS is calculated and displayed.
